 the book uses a 'class-relational' approach to analyse continuity and change in processes of accumulation, exploitation and domination. By focusing on the three interrelated arenas of labour relations, the state and civil society, it explores how improvements can be made in the conditions of labourers working 'at the margins' of global production networks, primarily as agricultural labourers and construction workers. Elements of social policy can improve the poor's material conditions and expand their political space where such ends are actively pursued by labouring class organisations. More fundamental change, though, requires stronger organisation of the informal workers who make up the majority of India's population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndustrial relationsxIndia. 0aIndustrial relationszIndia. 0aPovertyxIndia. 0aPovertyzIndia. 0aRural poorzIndia. 0aSocial classesxIndia. 0aSocial classeszIndia. 0aSocial sciences and statezIndia. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  aCivil Society.  aClass Relations.  aCommunity-based organisations.  aLabour.  aLocal Government Institutions.  aMarxism.  aNeoliberalism.  aRural India.  aSocial movements.  aState.1 aPattenden, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499702140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997021/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles